article.description:
Louisiana Tech guard Tasha Williams was clearly in 
pain, limping around the court every time the whistle blew.
article.headline: Florida St. capitalizes on guard's injury, beats Louisiana Tech
article.linkText: Florida State pushes pace, runs past Louisiana Tech
article.story:
DENVER (AP) -- Louisiana Tech guard Tasha Williams was clearly in 
pain, limping around the court every time the whistle blew.

Florida State saw the weakness and took advantage.

Holly Johnson scored a career-high 25 points, Alicia Gladden
added 20 and Florida State used two big first-half runs to beat
Louisiana Tech 80-71 Saturday night in the first round of the NCAA
Tournament.

Florida State (20-9), the No. 6 seed, will play the winner of
Southeast Missouri State and Stanford in the San Antonio Region
Monday.

Louisiana Tech (26-5), the 11th seed, was led by Tamika Kursh's
12 points and had its 12-game winning streak snapped.

The Seminoles dominated the boards, outrebounding the Lady
Techsters 48-37. Gladden had 12 rebounds and Ganiyat Adeduntan and
Nikki Anthony grabbed 10 apiece for Florida State.

"To outrebound them by 11 was the key to the game," said
Florida State coach Sue Semrau.

The Seminoles also managed to get to the free-throw line more
often than the Lady Techsters, hitting 19-of-32 shots. Louisiana
Tech was 14-of-20 from the line.

"I thought we had to keep them off the free-throw line," said
Louisiana Tech's first-year coach Chris Long. "We didn't do that.
That was basically the difference in the game."

Louisiana Tech, with 899 wins in school history, lost in the
first round for the second straight year and will have to wait
until next season to join Tennessee as the only women's programs
with 900 victories. The teams are the only schools to appear in all
25 NCAA Tournaments.

Williams, Louisiana Tech's point guard and second-leading scorer
with 13.1 points, injured her left foot in practice Wednesday and
was using a crutch to move around on Friday.

She played 35 minutes, but was clearly bothered by her foot. She
struggled to make cuts and was a step slow on defense.

"I wasn't mentally prepared," Williams said. "I'm not making
excuses. I just wasn't into the game, and that's the bottom line."

Williams, MVP of the Western Athletic Conference Tournament,
went down hard while covering Johnson, slapping the floor a couple
of times and grimacing when she got up midway through the second
half.

She returned and finished with four points, scoring her first
basket on a drive with just over 10 minutes remaining.

"That was a great effort by Tasha Williams," Semrau said. "To
play like that on an injured foot, she is a warrior."

Florida State hit seven 3-pointers and pushed the pace the
entire game, advancing to the second round for the second straight
year.

The Seminoles did it with runs of 12-0 and 11-4 in the first
half.

Adeduntan started the first run with a 3-pointer and capped it
with a short jumper to put Florida State up 26-16 with just over 11
minutes left. The Seminoles hit all five of their shots and
Louisiana Tech turned the ball over five times and missed its only
shot during the stretch.

Florida State, appearing in its sixth NCAA Tournament, ended the
first half with the 11-4 run to take a 43-32 lead at halftime.
Johnson keyed the run with five points, including a high-arching
3-pointer.

The senior guard was 4-of-8 from behind the arc.

"My teammates set up some great screens to get me open,"
Johnson said. "They looked to get me the ball, and I hit a couple
of 3's."
